title: For Sale:  Aimpoint Micro R-1 very good cond.
postcontent: I have a very good condition Aimpoint Micro R-1 I do not need anymore. It was on a project shotgun of mine that I traded for a pistol, and I do not have a weapon to put this on now nor do I believe I will be getting one anytime soon.I am the only owner of this, it was brand new in box when I bought it. It is "used" in that it was installed on my Remington 870 Tactical for the last few years - the vast majority of which it sat in the shotgun case/bag in the safe. I fired it a few hundred times - obviously only in the back yard and range, never took it into combat, never got into a shootout, never HAHO'ed into a hot LZ or inserted from a submarine on some SEAL mission. I put it on my HD shotgun and shot it some.It's in very good condition- not perfect, as there is a little wear mark here and there on the metal, nothing major but as I said, it's not "New In Box", it was installed on the gun for a few years. You can see the screw to the mount has been used a few times- that's the time of wear and marks I'm talking about, purely a little cosmetic age etc. Plus unless you plan on using this on a shotgun, you will need a mount of your desire, which will remove the base and screw anyway. (The included base is too low to use on any rifle setup. So you'd want a quality mount of various mfgrs and heights/styles/etc. I use Daniel Defense lower 1/3 mount on my other R-1 and M&P 15-22.) ---The glass is perfect however.If you are unfamiliar , this is one of the most highly respected and desired nonmagnified optics on the market. This has 12 brightness settings- on setting 8 of 12, a high-quality battery will give it FIVE YEARS OF CONSTANTLY ON BATTERY LIFE. Reducing the setting to 5 will give it EIGHT YEARS of CONSTANTLY ON BATTERY LIFE, and still a full year on maximum. Also, there are $1 generic cheap batteries you can find at the dollar stores which still give this at least a year of battery life CONSTANTLY ON. Aimpoint has the highest level of technological circuitry in optics on the planet and their construction/ruggedness is also legendary. These are professional, combat optics- the best of the best.It was a ~$550 piece of kit new. The only difference between this and the $600+ T-1 is the T-1 is black, and includes night-vision settings, the R-1 is silver and does not have the night-vision setting.Reduced to $375

He never even shot it once, eventually traded it to me, and I've had it out to the range about twice in the years I've had it, for a total of maybe 100 rounds (at most.)The rifle is dead-nuts accurate, and runs 100% perfectly. It's in very good condition, and comes with FIVE factory 10-round magazines, and the original owners manual.Also, though it's obviously in it's factory-original, unconverted state, I'm including most of the necessary conversion (and other) parts. There's a US-made telecscoping stock, a US-made pistol grip with mounting hardware, a set of US-made foregrips*, 2 new East-Bloc 30-round mil-surp steel magazines, two scope rails (one is a dual picatinny rail, the other with standard 1-inch rings), and a bullet guide from Dinzag (with mounting screw and receiver hole plugs).The only thing not included for the legal, hi-cap conversion is a Tapco G2 (or other brand) trigger group, that only runs around $25 last I checked. The price is the same whether you need the conversion parts or not, because.......well, because I obviously don't need them anymore either,LOL !!So, for those not familiar, the Saigas are widely considered among the highest quality AK variants you can buy,anywhere, being made in the same factory right along side the Russian military's Kalashnikovs, with genuine Russian receiver, chrome-lined barrel, and trigger group.
